srinivascodes: /*Returns least common multiple of two BigIntegers using gcd method*/.perceptron8: @srinivascodes I suspect this PR won't be merged anyway, so here's my two cents:

Do not check for equality using ==. Use equals instead. It's possible to construct BigInteger equal to BigInteger.ZERO but¬†not being the same instance as BigInteger.ZERO. One of many possibilities is to call new BigInteger(0, new byte[0]).
First divide, then multiply. It's more efficient. As rounding is indeed UNNECESSARY, don't use it at all (it is sufficient to use BigInteger.divide).
There's no need to call abs() more than once.

public static BigInteger lcm(BigInteger a, BigInteger b) {
	if (a.equals(BigInteger.ZERO) || b.equals(BigInteger.ZERO)) {
		return BigInteger.ZERO;
	}
	BigInteger gcd = a.gcd(b);
	return a.divide(gcd).multiply(b).abs();
}.srinivascodes: @perceptron8 Thanks for your valuable advice. Changed my code's implementation.
